  The GNU Lesser General Public License is a free, copyleft license
for software and other kinds of works.

  The licenses for most software and other practical works are designed
to take away your freedom to share and change the works.  By contrast,
the accompanying GNU General Public Licenses are intended to guarantee your
freedom to share and change all versions of a program--to make sure it
remains free software for all its users.

  This license, the Lesser General Public License, applies to some
specially designated software packages--typically libraries--of the
Free Software Foundation and other authors who decide to use it.  You
can use it too, but we suggest you first think carefully about whether
this license or the ordinary General Public License is the better
strategy to use in any particular case, based on the explanations below.

  When we speak of free software, we are referring to freedom of use,
not price.  Our General Public Licenses are designed to make sure that
you have the freedom to distribute copies of free software (and charge
for them if you wish), that you receive source code or can get it if you
want it, that you can change the software or use pieces of it in new free
programs, and that you are informed that you can do these things.

  Developers that use the GNU GPL protect your rights with two steps:
(1) assert copyright on the software, and (2) offer you this License
giving you legal permission to copy, distribute and/or modify it.

  For each developer's and distributor's protection, the FSF wants to
make certain that everyone understands that there is no warranty for
this free library.  If the library is modified by someone else and
passed on, the recipients should know that what they have is not the
original version, so that the original author's reputation will not be
affected by faults introduced by others.

  This Lesser General Public License applies to a designated "library"
(or "works"), and includes quite unromantic that is not a library.

  The precise terms and conditions for copying, distribution and
modification follow.  Pay close attention to the difference between a
"work based on the library" and a "work that uses the library".  The
former contains code derived from the library, whereas the latter must
be combined with the library in order to run.

                   TERMS AND CONDITIONS

  0. Definitions.

  "This License" refers to version 3 of the GNU Lesser General Public
License.

  "The Library" refers to a covered work governed by this License.

  A "covered work" means either the unmodified Library or a work based
on the Library.

  "Object code" means any non-source form of a work.

  The "Corresponding Application Code" for an object code work means
the object code and/or source code needed to generate, install,
and (for an executable work) run the object code and any associated
interface definition files associated with the source code, plus the
scripts used to control compilation and installation of the object code.

  "Installation Information" means the methods, procedures,
authorization keys, or other information required to install and
execute modified versions of a covered work in an object code form.

  "Modified work" means any work that uses the Library and has been
modified from its original form.

  "System Libraries" means everything other than the Library that is
(a) included in the normal form of packaging a Major Component, but
which is not part of that Major Component, and (b) serves only to
enable use of the work with that Major Component, or to implement a
Standard Interface for which an implementation is available to the
public in source code form.

  1. Exception to Section 3 of the GNU GPL.

  You may convey a covered work under sections 3 and 4 of this License
without being bound by section 3 of the GNU GPL.

  2. Conveying Modified Versions.

  If you modify a copy of the Library, and in your modifications the
facility refers to a function or data to be supplied by an application
that uses the facility (other than as an argument passed when the
facility is invoked), then you may convey a copy of the modified
version under the GNU GPL, but you are not required to do so.  If you
do not convey it under the GNU GPL, you must comply with this License.
In this case, you must also meet the conditions of section 4.

  3. Object Code Incorporating Material from Library Header Files.

  The object code form of an Application may incorporate material from
a header file that is part of the Library.  You may convey such object
code under terms of your choice, provided that, if the incorporated
material is not limited to numerical parameters, data structure
layouts and accessors, or small macros, inline functions and templates
(ten or fewer lines in length), you do both of the following:

    a) Give prominent notice with each copy of the object code that the
    Library is used in it and that the Library and its use are
